[1]
Date:14 Sep 2007
Source: Great Falls Tribune [edited]
<http://www.greatfallstribune.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20070913/NEWS01/70913018>

Antelope and whitetail deer in south eastern Montana dying of bluetongue
------------------------------------------------------------------------
Bluetongue, a gnatborne disease that causes animals to bleed to death
internally, is hitting antelope and whitetails in south eastern Montana.
Fish, Wildlife & Parks says the disease cannot be passed to humans but
suggests that hunters contact landowners to see if the disease is there.
So far "hundreds" of antelope and deer carcasses have been reported. The
heaviest concentration of the disease appears to be in the Melstone area
east to Ingomar and Sumatra. A hard frost will kill the gnats and biting
midges that carry the disease.
--
