[2]
Date: 13 Sep 2007
Source: Montana's News station [edited]
<http://www.montanasnewsstation.com/Global/story.asp?S=7072812&nav=menu227_2>

Disease blamed for wildlife deaths, suspected in livestock deaths
-----------------------------------------------------------------
A virus is blamed for some Montana wildlife deaths, and a state agency
suspecting the disease in Montana sheep is awaiting test results.
The state Department of Fish, Wildlife and Parks says bluetongue has been
confirmed in a white-tailed deer [a cervid] and an antelope [which is in
the family Bovidae, making it a bovine]. It's suspected in other recent
deer and antelope deaths in central and south eastern Montana. Another
state agency, the Department of Livestock, suspects bluetongue in sheep,
and is awaiting a laboratory report.
Early this week [17-21 Sep 2007], the department ordered that sheep
producers in Musselshell County not transport their animals for 30 days.
That restriction came after about 100 sheep in the county died during the
previous 2 weeks. The order against transportation is intended to reduce
the possible spread of bluetongue, which is transmitted by gnats.
The wildlife department says bluetongue is not a risk to human health.
--
