[3]
Date: 18 Sep 2007
Source: Montana's News Station [edited]
<http://www.montanasnewsstation.com/Global/story.asp?S=7092763&nav=menu227_2>

Bluetongue disease hitting parts of Montana
-------------------------------------------
An insectborne viral disease is spreading through central and south east
Montana and could affect archery hunters who are planning to travel through
the area.
Cases of bluetongue have been confirmed in one white tailed deer and an
antelope between Roundup and Miles City and in addition several hundred
deer and antelope near Melstone have died from the disease. Officials say
the virus causes quick and fatal internal hemorrhaging and is transmitted
through biting gnats.
We spoke Ron Aasheim with Montana Fish, Wildlife and Parks who says that
archery hunters should check with local landowners for hunting
opportunities because deer and antelope harvest occurs on private land.
Bluetongue does not affect humans either through contact, or consumption of
infected animals.
--
